@NODE "Important" "Important"
@WORDWRAP
@{U}@{B}Important:@{UU}@{UB}

@{B}WinBack III @{U}cannot@{UU} restore compressed backups:@{UB}
- Turn compression @{B}off@{UB} (options menu) in Windows Backup before
  making your backups ...

@{B}WinBack III doesn't restore directories@{UB}, it only restores files...
- if you want to keep the directory-tree your files are in (on the PC), you have to pack it using WinZip (or another similar tool) and backup the compressed file. Restore the file on the Amiga (using WinBack III) and unpack it. You dir-tree is intact...

@{B}Using volume names instead of device names for source paths may cause problems:@{UB}
  see @{"   bugs   " LINK "bugs"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Bugs" "Bugs"
@WORDWRAP
Known bugs:

Using volume names when specifying the source file will cause problems in a multidisk backup when the disks have different names...

Solution: don't use volume names, use device names (PC0: - PC1: - ...)
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Background" "Background"
@WORDWRAP
For years I've been downloading megabytes of stuff from Aminet at work, and for years I've been using Mikael Nordlund's PC-Restore to backup those gigantic files that didn't fit the 720k PC-formatted disks.
Then one day I accidentally deleted the old MS-DOS backup-program, and I was stuck: PC-restore could only restore files from this backup-program and didn't support the backup-program supplied with Windows 95.
I surfed the internet to find an Amiga-program that could restore those Windows-backups, but I couldn't find one...

Well, there was only one thing to do: write it myself...
@ENDNODE
